summary:
Did you ever asked yourself which character was the strongest ? Here is the answer from Kevin Feige himself. 
“She is more...
caption:
Did you ever asked yourself which character was the strongest ? Here is the answer from Kevin Feige himself.

“She is more powerful than any character we’ve introduced thus far. So that alone tells you that there’s a reason Nick hit that button at the end [of Infinity War], when he realized that they were up against something far bigger than they had ever been up against before. And having her on your side is hopefully going to change the balance of power in a way that they desperately need.”

Si vous vous demandiez qui est le personnage le plus puissant du Marvel Cinematic Universe, je vous conseille de continuer la lecture ✌️

“[Captain Marvel] est plus puissante que n'importe quel autre personnage que l'on a déjà introduit. Juste ça, vous permet de comprendre la raison pour laquelle Nick a appuyé sur ce bouton à la fin d’ Avengers: Infinity War, lorsqu'il comprend qu'il est face à quelque chose de beaucoup trop grand, beaucoup trop puissant. Et l'avoir à ses cotés va, on l'espère, modifier dans le bon sens l'équilibre des forces”
- Kevin Feige

title: Shadow-boxed
body:
They’re on a stakeout and she’s trapped with Carol in a 6 x 10 room and Carol’s stuck with her, and this is the exact wrong moment for the awaking of latent lesbian urges. Jessica’s used to her body going out of wack on her and the way it usually backfires on others, but this is a new brand of personal hell.

Post-The Enemy Within character study fic. Jessica is sad, Carol doesn’t remember anything. They don’t deal with it. Unresolved sexual tension stays unresolved.

Written for @caroljessshipevents Carol/Jess Mini Bang 2018, with an amazing illustration from @jayjayverse (check it out)!

summary: Dear White Women: A Rising Tide Does NOT Lift All Boats
title: Dear White Women: A Rising Tide Does NOT Lift All Boats
body:
A few days ago, Entertainment Weekly released the cover of their upcoming issue with Brie Larson as Captain Marvel on it. It’s the first official, official tissue look at the costume and Larson as the iconic Carol Danvers, and people are understandably losing their shit. 10+ plus years later, and Marvel finally seems ready for a female-lead superhero movie, and that’s awesome. If I’m being completely honest, the lack of gender parity is part of the reason I stopped watching Marvel movies after Ant-Man (except for Black Panther, of course).

With that being said, before this gets out of control again, I want to re-hash a point that I and many others made back when Wonder Woman was making its rounds…Keep Reading
